When you drink liquid protein, the sphincter stays open. The protein is inefficiently processed.
So if you want to drink liquid protein, eat something solid first so that your stomach works right.

As a swim coach for a university here is my general advice.

>Strength
Keep doing compounds and try 5x5. Try to make the progression from 1-5 consistent and even, the 5th set you should struggle to finish. When it gets easy add a little bit of weight over the whole set (Example 5 lbs to each set of 5). This is called progressive overload. You'll get stronger over time, soreness is a good indicator if you worked hard enough.

>Agility
Assuming by the fact you are naturally not very coordinated you really cant overcome that with just training. But you can try programs like plyometrics (box jumps, one legged hops) to learn your body a bit better. Think of movement as transference of energy from one section to another, if you are stiff and there are moments where you "catch" and lock out at a wrong time try to make it feel more smooth.

Best of luck -Swim bro
